    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About ACV Gummies for Weight Loss</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Do ACV gummies actually help with weight loss?</summary><p>The evidence is limited but modestly positive. A 2009 study found that 30mL vinegar daily for 12 weeks produced 3.7 lbs additional weight loss. However, most ACV gummies provide only 7-13% of this dose. They may provide a small metabolic advantage when combined with a caloric deficit and exercise.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much acetic acid do ACV gummies contain?</summary><p>Most provide 50-100mg acetic acid per serving (1,000mg ACV at 5% acetic acid). The clinical weight loss study used 750mg acetic acid daily — 7-15x higher. This dose gap is the fundamental limitation of ACV gummies.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are ACV gummies as effective as liquid ACV?</summary><p>Gummies deliver significantly less acetic acid per serving. One tablespoon of liquid ACV contains ~750mg acetic acid; two gummies contain ~50-100mg. However, gummies offer better compliance — consistent daily use may outperform sporadic liquid use.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>When should I take ACV gummies for weight loss?</summary><p>Take 20-30 minutes before your two largest meals. A 2014 study found that pre-meal vinegar reduced the glycemic response by 20-40% and increased satiety, potentially reducing subsequent caloric intake by 200-275 calories.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long do ACV gummies take to work for weight loss?</summary><p>The clinical study used 12 weeks and showed 0.3 lbs/week additional loss. Allow 8-12 weeks of consistent daily use with a caloric deficit before evaluating results. ACV gummies are a minor metabolic enhancer, not a primary weight loss tool.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do ACV gummies have side effects?</summary><p>Generally well-tolerated. Possible effects: mild digestive discomfort, nausea on empty stomach, acid reflux in GERD-prone individuals. Gummies reduce tooth enamel erosion risk versus liquid ACV. Most contain 2-4g sugar per serving.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What should I look for in ACV gummies for weight loss?</summary><p>At least 500mg ACV per gummy, "the mother" included, added B-vitamins or antioxidants, low sugar (2g or less), third-party testing, and organic certification if sourcing matters to you.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take ACV gummies while intermittent fasting?</summary><p>Most ACV gummies have 10-15 calories per serving. For strict water-only fasts, liquid ACV is better. For modified fasting protocols allowing 50 calories, ACV gummies fit within the threshold without significantly impacting results.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> ACV gummies are not a substitute for evidence-based weight management approaches: caloric deficit, regular exercise, adequate protein intake, and sufficient sleep. No supplement can compensate for these fundamentals. If you are struggling with significant weight loss goals, consult a registered dietitian or physician who can develop a personalized plan. Individuals with gastroparesis, GERD, or diabetes should consult their physician before taking ACV supplements.</p>
    </div>

